PhD Proposal (Version 4)

Microtubule-Inspired Distributed Intelligence Architectures for Autonomous Spacecraft Systems

Author: Ouadi Maakoul
Proposed Field: Artificial Intelligence • Complex Systems • Space Systems Engineering • Soft Robotics

---

Abstract

This purely theoretical PhD replaces centralized spacecraft computers with a microtubule-inspired cognitive hull whose intelligence scales with coordination capacity rather than CPU flops. We develop a rigorous mathematical framework for distributed intelligence embedded directly into spacecraft structures: a lattice of coupled nodes, each combining sensing, actuation, and local processing. The central hypothesis is formalized as an analytical scaling law: adaptive behavior complexity C scales with coordination capacity \mathcal{K} = \lambda_2(L)\, B\, \tau^{-1}, where \lambda_2(L) is algebraic connectivity, B is information bandwidth per edge, and \tau is response time. This contrasts with centralized architectures limited by communication bottlenecks and single-point failures.

Key theoretical contributions include: (1) stability theorems for bidirectional oscillator-elasticity coupling using Lyapunov methods and spectral graph theory, establishing synchronization rates bounded by algebraic connectivity; (2) rigorous derivation of the scaling law C \propto \mathcal{K}^\alpha \log N via information diffusion on graphs and quantized wave modes; (3) analytical bounds on embodied information throughput I_{\text{emb}} = \sum_{i,j} I(a_i; s_j) relating it to coordination capacity; (4) variational morphological optimization framework deriving Euler-Lagrange equations for optimal physical parameters (coupling strengths, stiffness, actuation amplitudes) that maximize global objectives; and (5) spectral topology design principles proving optimal lattice architectures for given constraints. The framework directly addresses gaps identified in the 2025 Motile Active Matter Roadmap and extends NASA Starling DSA from software coordination to physical-substrate intelligence. All results are analytical, providing mathematically optimal blueprints ready for future engineering realization.

