2. Related Work and Gap Analysis

2.1 Coupled Oscillator Networks

The Kuramoto model (1975) and its lattice extensions (Strogatz, 2000) establish synchronization conditions but assume passive coupling without actuation or learning. Recent work on adaptive couplings (Wang & Dong, J. Differential Equations, 2025) introduces time-varying connections but lacks bidirectional elasticity feedback. Liu et al. (Scientific Reports, 2024) analyze symmetry-breaking in oscillator lattices via Laplacian eigenvectors, while cluster synchronization results (Chaos, 2025) provide spectral conditions. Gap: None include bidirectional coupling between phase and deformation, nor derive scaling laws linking coordination capacity to adaptive behavior.

2.2 Active Matter and Programmable Materials

Active matter physics (Toner & Tu, 1998; Vicsek et al., 1995) studies emergent order in self-propelled particles. The 2025 Motile Active Matter Roadmap (Gompper et al., J. Phys.: Condens. Matter, 2025) explicitly calls for "intelligent active materials" and "collective actuation in confinement" that can adapt to goals. Programmable materials (Hawkes et al., 2010) achieve shape changes under global control. Gap: No existing work embeds distributed intelligence with morphological optimization in a lattice, nor provides analytical scaling laws for adaptive capacity.

2.3 Embodied Intelligence

Recent theoretical frameworks (Baulin, arXiv:2502.13224, 2025; Foundations of Embodied Intelligence for Robotic Systems, Found. Trends Robotics, 2025) treat morphology as a passive constraint on learning. Gupta et al. (2021) incorporate body dynamics but not active morphological optimization. Gap: We derive active morphological optimization coupled to oscillator dynamics, with information-theoretic bounds on embodied intelligence.

2.4 Distributed Spacecraft Autonomy

NASA's Starling mission (Adams et al., NASA NTRS, 2024; Hunter, 2025) demonstrates distributed software coordination for swarm autonomy via protocols like ROMEO and DSA (Distributed Spacecraft Autonomy). These provide theoretical MILP solvers for software coordination on separate processors. Gap: Our framework derives analytical scaling laws for intelligence embedded in the physical hull itself—the substrate becomes the processor.

2.5 Morphological Computation

Ben Zion et al. (Science Robotics, 2023) demonstrate passive morphological computation via steric interactions in "Morphobots." Gap: Theirs is passive and mechanical; ours is active and analytically optimized through variational principles.

